Ringleader Putin
Medical experts from Moscow, Germany, France, and Sweden all agree: Alexei Navalny is the victim of the Novichok nerve agent. Navalny is Russia's largest opposition figure and also the founder of the anti-corruption foundation.
Luckily, Navalny's survival prevented Russia and Germany relations from deteriorating.
German Chancellor Merkel announced that Navalny is a "victim of persecution due to freedom of speech" in order to demonstrate her "clear position".
In her view, this incident is extremely serious, and only the Russian government can and must respond.
She emphasized that the whole world needs an explanation.
Merkel calls on the Russian authorities to conduct an independent and transparent investigation.
The European Union and the United Kingdom also support this call.
If the results of the investigation prove that the Russian government is the mastermind behind the event, the European Commission will impose new sanctions.
Regardless of this, based on the convention of the Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons, poisoning is a prohibited behavior.
This is not the first time the Putin government has used the Novichok nerve agent to target its political opponents.
In 2018, Russian former double agent Sergei Skripal and his daughter Yulia were poisoned on British soil.
Both survived and went into hiding.
The Kremlin strongly denies both incidents.
Regarding the Navalny incident, Kremlin spokesperson Dmitry Peskov firmly claimed "there is no evidence to implicate the Russian government."
Russian Foreign Intelligence Director Sergei Naryshkin even said that this is the behavior of Western intelligence agencies, to blame the Russian government for this.
Naryshkin's statement is obviously an excuse, but he also said a fact: the Navalny incident is detrimental to Russia.
Before the upcoming election, poisoning a famous political opponent, and using a poison developed by the former Soviet Union, is hard to explain.
Especially at a time when the Belarusian people are protesting the upcoming August election, the timing is more puzzling.
And the Kremlin's initial reaction to the Navalny incident was also particularly confusing.
Shouldn't the Russian government have planned more carefully before committing a crime?
If it's indeed the Russian government, as Germany claims, this assassination attempt was also a failed one.
Putin has always been the Darth Vader of international politics, interfering in the US elections, inciting street protests in France, manipulating the UK's Brexit, and supporting Bashar al-Assad in Syria.
As a former KGB agent, he is intelligent, far-sighted, and cunning.
So why can't he kill Skripal and Navalny?
Why can Navalny escape to Germany? And he was quickly diagnosed with poisoning?
Now, Putin faces international condemnation and sanctions, and the Nord Stream 2 natural gas pipeline project to Germany is facing cancellation.
This assassination attempt is clearly not worth it.
After all, it has only further incited the people to resist the evil deeds of the Russian authorities.
Even if it's not Putin's doing, the accusation that it was Western intelligence agencies is even more outrageous.
If such an accusation is true, scientists from Germany and Sweden would not have spoken of the fact of the Novichok nerve agent.
More likely it came from Putin's political circle of conspirators.
Perhaps Putin needs Navalny to shut up before the election, or perhaps he has gotten in trouble with his anti-corruption investigation.
In Russia, you can buy various products and services on the black market, including military-grade nerve agents.
Putin's political hitmen may be loyal but stupid, they thought poisoning Navalny was a good idea, only a few who participated knew the truth.
Other failed poisoning operations share similar characteristics: the poisoning of journalist Vladimir Kara-Murza in 2015 and 2017. Kara-Murza is the coordinator of the Hrodzensky Committee, which publicly investigates the case.
The poisoning of independent news website Mediazona's publisher Peter Verzilov in 2018.
Mediazona is a website that reports on Russia's judicial abuse of power.
Further back, it can be traced to 2006, the poisoning of former KGB agent Alexander Litvinenko, who often criticized the Russian security agencies.
As in the Navalny case, such poisoning often has a boomerang effect.
2004, liberal newspaper "Novaya Gazeta" columnist Anna Politkovskaya was poisoned on a plane from Moscow to Beslan, though she survived, but was shot dead in her apartment's elevator two years later.
As Putin said, her death brought huge harm to the image of the Russian government.
This is not to excuse the Kremlin in any way.
Whether Putin personally commanded it or not, the system he created allowed such crimes to occur. Such a system is both ineffective and pointless, and is just a farce involving some despicable actors.
Navalny's death is the result that the Kremlin wanted, and the ultimate goal of the yes-men is to make Putin happy.
In the circle of Putin, loyalty is the only goal.
Even if the poisoning fails, they will not face punishment.
Because they did it for the benefit of the president.
Those who are looking for evidence of the poisoning might be disappointed.
Regardless of that, the Kremlin is the mastermind.
Western countries must make it clear that even if their own economy is affected, they must take sanctions against Russia.
Putin has created a system centered on Putin.
All the responsibilities in Russia are attributed to him.
